title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 870 Police Magnum
postcontent:
18" barrel with magazine extension for a 6+1 capacity. Shoots 2 3/4" and 3" shells. Has rifle sights also. This is an actual police gun used by a police department and shows signs of use. This gun was made to work and it functions as it should, you will not find a better gun for home defense. I added a list below of some of the major differences between the police and express guns just to give those of you who dont know why the police versions are more desirable. 

 The 870 Police has:
- An aluminum trigger group (vs plastic on the 870 express).
- Old style magazine retention system (you can add mag extension w/o modification) 
- The Police gun receives a higher level of inspection and finishing and is built in a special area of the plant from 100% inspected parts.
- A military-grade parkerized finish.
- A polished bore.
- A one piece barrel.
- A short police-length fore end. 
- The Remington “R3” super recoil pad that reduces felt recoil by 30%.
- Sling swivels.
- Heavy-duty magazine spring to ensure positive shell feeding.
- Heavy-duty trigger-sear spring. to reduce the chance of accidental fire
- Heavy-duty shell lifter spring which also improves positive feeding.
- No use of MIM parts, the extractor is milled
- Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety.
- The receivers used in Police guns are “vibra honed” to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization or bluing.
- High visibility follower.

postcontent:
The 241 tac con trigger has three sector options.  Safe, "forced trigger reset" and normal "precision mode" 
In the forced reset mode the hammer pushes the trigger forward a little and helps with rapid fire shooting.  With a little practice you can bump fire in normal holding position. 

I just bought this trigger and it works great and as advertised but with my shooting style it's not for me.  
You have to hold the rifle very loose to have it bump back and forth. I just don't like that style of shooting. 

It's a very well build trigger, very very easy to install. Just not for me.  It has only seen 100 rounds.

location: La Mirada, Ca, Orange County, California
postcontent:
For Sale: M1 Garand Springfield Armory M1 Rifle NM-1 (Type-1) SN: 5809XXX dated: 2-55

(Information below was taken from an NRA article on NM Garand's. I added a few “added notes” as to this Rifle for your information.)
Between 1953-1955 Springfield Armory produced the first of the NM series rifles the NM-1 (Type-1), serial numbers will be between approximately 5,800,000 and 6,100,000. 
Most of the unaltered original Type 1 NM rifles will exhibit the following characteristics
-Markings on right receiver leg: Drawing number, “6528287-SA;” Heat Lot, T 1 to T 10 - Z 5 to Z15 (added note: This Rifle receiver drawing no: F6528291 Heat lot; Z6A, Which matches Springfield Armory records for NM receiver. Left side receiver is stamped with "S")
-Barrel: Marked “T” for (targeted); “P” for (proofed); “SA F6535448” (Add Note: This Barrel is marked "SA F 6525448 drawing number with two "S" stamps over the F); Month and year of barrel production; Heat lot code, “m” (magnetic particle testing) and Defense Acceptance Stamp (Added Note: This Rifle has additional inverted "P" with punch mark center "P" loop which was used as early NM marking).
-Bolt: “6522887-SA” (with heat lot code) (Added Note: This rifle Bolt "6528287-SA)
-Windage Knob: “DRC”
-Elevation Knob: “WCE” (Added Note: This rifle has "DRC" Elevation Knob)
""It should be noted that the early production examples (1953-1955) may have different parts from those listed above."" Stocks for NM-1 Rifles were not glassed, but rather hand selected for tight fit and uniform wood grain.
Springfield Armory engineers and armors worked closely to prefect the Nation Match 1 rifle.  
The exact number of Type 1 National Match rifles made is unknown. There is a much-published chart purporting to give a breakdown of M1 National Match production from 1953 to 1963. 

This is a rare find for the shooters or collector. NM-1's are rare in this condition.

Note: Buyer Pays: Shipping and DOJ registration fees
I will consider reasonable offers. 

This is a nice accurate shooting rifle in excellent condition and all the marking as stated above.. For Shooter or Collector. Rare find!
